# Current version
# v4.0
# 11/14/2025
# 
# Format: tdar [-s, or -p] <file_name> [field_name] [date]
# The -s (skip), and -p (print-out) flags, along with field_name and date, are optional.
# file_name is required.
# file_name must be entered in its entirety.
# file_name MUST be the first argument or immediately follow any flags used.
# Date MUST be in the mmddyyyy format.
#
# Users can use periods, slashes, or dashes to separate the month, day, and year, 
# as long as it maintains the mmddyyyy structure.
# Valid single-date examples:
#   11.13.2025
#   11-13-2025
#   11/13/2025
#
# --------------------------------------------
# DATE RANGE FORMAT
# --------------------------------------------
#
# To specify a range of dates, wrap the range in braces:
#       {mmddyyyy:mmddyyyy}
#
# You may use any separator (periods, slashes, or dashes) as long as the structure
# remains mmddyyyy.
#
# Valid examples:
#   {11.02.2025:11.09.2025}
#   {11-02-2025:11-09-2025}
#   {11/02/2025:11/09/2025}
#
# --------------------------------------------
# FLAG OPTIONS
# --------------------------------------------
#
# Use the "-s" flag to skip the detailed per-date listing and only display the 
# complete totals of the file.
# Example:
#       tdar -s <file_name> [field_name] [date_or_range]
#
# Use the "-p" flag to print the results of the command into a text file.
# Example:
#       tdar -p <file_name> [field_name] [date_or_range]
#
# When using "-p", the script will prompt the user for a store number.
# The created file will be named:
#       "Results for <store_number> [field_name] [date_or_range].txt"
#
# The -s and -p flags may be used together.
#
# --------------------------------------------
# ARGUMENT BEHAVIOR
# --------------------------------------------
#
# field_name is optional.
#   - If provided, only that field will be totaled.
#   - If omitted, all fields will be included.
#
# date/date_range is optional.
#   - If provided, tdar shows data ONLY for that day or range.
#   - If omitted, tdar processes the entire file.
#
# Valid order of optional arguments:
#   <file_name> [field_name] [date_or_range]
#
# --------------------------------------------
# EXAMPLES
# --------------------------------------------
#
# Entire file:
#       tdar testDAR.json
#
# Single date:
#       tdar testDAR.json 10-20-2025
#       tdar testDAR.json TotalSales 10/20/2025
#
# Date range:
#       tdar testDAR.json {10-20-2025:10-27-2025}
#       tdar testDAR.json TotalSales {10/20/2025:10/27/2025}
#
# Skip totals only:
#       tdar -s testDAR.json TotalSales
#
# Print output to file:
#       tdar -p testDAR.json TotalSales 10-20-2025
#
# Print + skip:
#       tdar -p -s testDAR.json TotalSales {11/02/2025:11/09/2025}
